<h2>
   Top Bass Waters Around Bend
</h2>
<h3>
    Crane Prairie Reservoir (~45 mins)
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Largemouth heaven among lily pads, stumps, and reedbeds. Trophy-quality fish (4–6 lb) are common.
    </li>
    <li>
        Best April–July: fish shallow flats, sun-warmed bays with soft plastic worms, jigs, or topwater lures.&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    Prineville Reservoir (~1 hr)
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Clear, deep lake holding both largemouth and smallmouth, along with trout and crappie. Bank and boat options abound.&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    Haystack Reservoir (~55 min)
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Known more for smallmouth but also trout; scenic surroundings and public boat ramps. <a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="https://anglerscrate.com/best-largemouth-bass-fishing-spots-in-oregon/?utm_source=chatgpt.com">anglerscrate.com</a>
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    Lake Billy Chinook (~1h)
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Wraps around the Deschutes, Crooked, and Metolius arms—excellent bass action spring through fall.&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    Davis Lake (~45 min)
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Hidden bass fishery with leech reports from local shops; spring topwater action is strong.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    Wickiup Reservoir (~40 min)
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Primarily a trout lake, but clear seasonal holds of bass exist.&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Bank vs Boat Fishing
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Bank Fishing</strong>: Easy access at Prineville, Haystack, and Crane Prairie’s north shore. Crane Prairie offers marshy flats ideal for shore anglers.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Boats/Kayaks</strong>: Expand access to deep flats and stretch farther into reservoirs—essential for productive Crane Prairie outings.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Gear &amp; Techniques for Bass Success
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Rod/Reel</strong>: 6’6″–7′ medium-heavy casting rod with 12–20 lb braid or mono; low-profile baitcaster or 2500 spinning reel.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Top Lures</strong>:
        <ul>
            <li>
                <strong>Spring/Early Summer</strong>: Frogs, poppers, soft plastics (Senko, creature baits). 
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Summer</strong>: Spinnerbaits, surface poppers in morning/evening.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Fall</strong>: Deep crankbaits, drop-shot rigs, jig trailers.
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Tips</strong>: Match lure size and color to water clarity—natural shades for clear water, bold patterns in stained water.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Family-Friendly Bass Spots
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Davis Lake</strong>: Fly-shop reports for leech and small bass action—kid-friendly and accessible.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Prineville Reservoir and Haystack</strong>: Easy boat ramps and camping for family outings.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Shevlin &amp; Pine Nursery Ponds</strong> in Bend: Rainbow trout stocked but also occasional smallmouth—perfect for teaching kids.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Regulations &amp; Licenses
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Oregon angling license</strong> required for ages 12+. 
    </li>
    <li>
        Standard <strong>bass bag and size limits</strong> apply—check ODFW for each waterbody.
    </li>
    <li>
        All waters open to bait and lures (check exceptions at fly-only lakes).
    </li>
</ul>
